@@ -1939,10 +1939,10 @@ <h2>Deterministic Replay — Same Ops, Same Slots, Every Time</h2>
         When debugging a concurrency bug in tokio or async-std, you're at the mercy of non-deterministic scheduling.
         Run the same test twice and you get different behavior. Asupersync's handle allocator uses a
         <strong style="color:var(--text);">deterministic LIFO free-list</strong> — the same sequence of
-        create/close operations <em>always</em> produces identical slot assignments. This means you can
-        <strong style="color:var(--text);">replay a failing execution exactly</strong>, down to every handle slot
-        and generation counter. This demo runs the same 15-operation sequence twice and proves byte-for-byte
-        identical allocation.
+        create/close operations always produces the same <em>relative</em> allocation pattern.
+        This demo runs the same 13-operation sequence (create 5, close 3, create 5 more) twice
+        in separate runtimes and compares the slot offset patterns. The LIFO reuse order is identical
+        every time — which slots get recycled and in what order is fully deterministic.
       </p>
